# Tutorial State Firebase Migration

## Current Implementation

The overlay tutorial "seen" state is currently stored in **localStorage** with a userId-based key:

```typescript
const STORAGE_KEY = `overlay-tutorial-seen:${userId}`;
```

This approach:
- Works with the current placeholder userId (`'dev-user-placeholder'`) during development
- Will automatically use the real Firebase UID once auth is properly implemented
- Keeps tutorial state per-user on the same device
- Does NOT persist across devices or after browser data is cleared

## Files Involved

- `packages/ui/src/composables/useTutorialState.ts` - The composable managing tutorial state
- `packages/ui/src/components/OverlayTutorial.vue` - The tutorial UI component
- `packages/ui/src/components/OverlayEditor.vue` - Integration point that triggers tutorial

## Migration Steps (When Firebase Auth is Ready)

### 1. Update the User Type

Add the tutorial seen flag to the User type in `packages/types/src/user.ts`:

```typescript
export interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  // ... other fields
  hasSeenOverlayTutorial: boolean; // Add this
}
```

### 2. Create User Service Functions

Add functions to `packages/services/src/users/index.ts`:

```typescript
export async function getUserPreferences(userId: string) {
  const doc = await getDoc(doc(db, 'users', userId));
  return doc.data();
}

export async function setTutorialSeen(userId: string) {
  await updateDoc(doc(db, 'users', userId), {
    hasSeenOverlayTutorial: true
  });
}
```

### 3. Update the Composable

Replace localStorage with Firestore in `useTutorialState.ts`:

```typescript
import { getUserPreferences, setTutorialSeen } from '@guidenav/services';

export function useTutorialState(userId: string) {
  const hasSeenTutorial = ref(false);
  const loading = ref(true);
  
  onMounted(async () => {
    // Migrate from localStorage if exists
    const localKey = `overlay-tutorial-seen:${userId}`;
    const localValue = localStorage.getItem(localKey);
    
    if (localValue === 'true') {
      await setTutorialSeen(userId);
      localStorage.removeItem(localKey);
      hasSeenTutorial.value = true;
    } else {
      const prefs = await getUserPreferences(userId);
      hasSeenTutorial.value = prefs?.hasSeenOverlayTutorial ?? false;
    }
    loading.value = false;
  });
  
  async function markTutorialSeen() {
    await setTutorialSeen(userId);
    hasSeenTutorial.value = true;
  }
  
  return { hasSeenTutorial, markTutorialSeen, loading };
}
```

### 4. Update Firestore Security Rules

Ensure users can read/write their own tutorial preference:

```javascript
match /users/{userId} {
  allow read, write: if request.auth.uid == userId;
}
```

## Why This Temporary Approach?

Firebase Authentication is not yet fully implemented in this project. The `useAuth()` composable currently returns a placeholder user ID. Using localStorage with the userId as a key allows:

1. The feature to work during development
2. Automatic user-scoped storage once real auth is added
3. A clear migration path documented here
